# BLOCK 6 — THE LEAD EXTRACTION COMMAND

Here’s the command again:

```powershell
Import-Csv ".\research\leads\enriched_solano_crm_database.csv" |
Where-Object { $_.company_name -notlike "*Research*" } |
Format-Table company_name, sector, city, phone, website
```

Now let’s decode it piece-by-piece.

---

# LINE 1 — IMPORT THE DATABASE

```powershell
Import-Csv
```

Meaning:

> “Open the spreadsheet and read all the rows.”

---

# LINE 2 — THE FILE LOCATION

```powershell
".\research\leads\enriched_solano_crm_database.csv"
```

The `.\` means:

> “Start from the folder I’m currently inside.”

Since you already used:

```powershell
cd "C:\Users\arthu\GeminiEcosystem\PrimePathwyOS"
```

…it now knows where to begin.

---

# LINE 3 — THE PIPE SYMBOL

```powershell
|
```

This is called a pipe.

Think of it like an assembly line.

```text
Step 1 output
    ↓
gets sent into
    ↓
Step 2
```

---

# LINE 4 — FILTERING THE BAD ROWS

```powershell
Where-Object
```

Meaning:

> “Only show rows matching my conditions.”

---

# THIS PART:

```powershell
$_.company_name
```

Means:

> “Look at the company_name column for each row.”

---

# THIS PART:

```powershell
-notlike "*Research*"
```

Means:

> “Remove fake placeholder research rows.”

So the command is filtering your CRM down to real targets only.

---

# LINE 5 — DISPLAY THE RESULTS

```powershell
Format-Table
```

Meaning:

> “Display the data cleanly in columns.”

---

# THESE ARE THE COLUMNS YOU CHOSE

```powershell
company_name
sector
city
phone
website
```

So instead of seeing messy raw spreadsheet data…

…you get a readable business target list.

